Yam was elected to the Chinese Academy of Sciences in 2001, becoming the youngest member.<ref name=Ahmed2013>{{cite journal|last=Ahmed|first=Farooq|title=Profile of Vivian W.-W. Yam|journal=PNAS|date=May 14, 2013|volume=110|issue=20|doi=10.1073|url=http://www.pnas.org/content/110/20/7964.full|accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref> The previous holder of this record was Yam's previous mentor.<ref name=Ahmed2013/> She was elected a Fellow of the [[TWAS|Academy of Sciences for the Developing World]] in 2006 and a member of the Foreign Associate of [[National Academy of Sciences]] in 2012.<ref name=LIFM /> 

==Application==
Yam's research is no pure research but has had recent and aspiring applications. Yam sees the problem of humanity's power consumption as a significant issue and her chemistry has enabled much more efficient displays to be created for mobile phones and laptops. Her work has been used [[organic light emitting diodes]] which are brighter and more efficient that the older light emitting diodes. These [[OLED]]s can be deposited on clear plastic, glass or more unusual materials to also create improved car headlamps and larger flat television screens. Yam quotes that nearly a fifth of the world's power is used to create lighting. Creating more efficient lighting will significantly effect the world's power consumption. She believes the internal quantum theory indicates that we may develop lamps based on metal containing chemicals that are 100% efficient.<ref name=Ahmed2013/>

==Other awards==
Her awards include the HKU Outstanding Researcher Award (1999-2000), Croucher Foundation Senior Research Fellow (2000-01), Ten Outstanding Young Persons of Hong Kong in 2002, Outstanding Women Professionals and Entrepreneurs Awards (2005), State Natural Science Award (Second Class Prize, 2005), the Royal Society of Chemistry Centenary Lectureship & Medal (2005/06), and the Japanese Photochemistry Association Lectureship Award for Asian and Oceanian Photochemist (Eikohsha Award, (2006), HKU Distinguished Research Achievement Award (2006/07), Hong Kong Outstanding Women Professionals and Entrepreneurs Award (2008), Ho Leung Ho Lee Foundation Prize for Scientific and Technological Progress (2011), L<U+2019>OREAL-UNESCO for Women in Science Award (2011), and the 13th World Outstanding Chinese Award (2013).<ref name=croucher>{{cite web|title=Professor Vivian YAM Wing Wah|url=http://www.croucher.org.hk/professor-vivian-yam-wing-wah|publisher=Croucher Foundation|accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=LIFM />

Yam was particularly pleased to receive the L<U+2019>OREAL-UNESCO for Women in Science Award in 2011 which established her as a role model for other female scientists. Yam encourages younger aspiring scientific women to ignore the cultural and family pressures and to concentrate on their own ambitions.<ref name=Ahmed2013/>

